" ============================================================================
"   These are the "live wires" that carry data between functions across time:
"
"   ┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
"   │  s:current_chat_job                                                     │
"   │                                                                         │
"   │  Set by ── SendChatMessage()      (job handle / channel)                │
"   │            FinalImplementResponse() also clears it                      │
"   │  Read by ── CancelClaudeResponse()  (to stop the job)                   │
"   │  Cleared by FinalChatResponse()  /  CancelClaudeResponse()              │
"   │             FinalImplementResponse()                                    │
"   └─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
"
"   ┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
"   │  s:implement_response                                                   │
"   │                                                                         │
"   │  Created & grown by ── StreamingImplementResponse()  (delta by delta)   │
"   │  Consumed by ────────── FinalImplementResponse()                        │
"   │                           └─ LogImplementInChat()                       │
"   │                           └─ ExtractCodeFromMarkdown()                  │
"   │  Deleted by ─────────── FinalImplementResponse()                        │
"   └─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
"
"   ┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
"   │  s:current_tool_call   { id, name, input }                              │
"   │                                                                         │
"   │  Created by ── HandleStreamOutput()  on content_block_start (tool_use)  │
"   │  Grown by ──── HandleStreamOutput()  on input_json_delta                │
"   │  Consumed by ─ HandleStreamOutput()  on content_block_stop              │
"   │                  └─ AppendToolUse()  (writes to chat buffer)            │
"   │  Deleted by ── HandleStreamOutput()  on content_block_stop              │
"   │                                                                         │
"   │  Lifetime: one tool call within one streaming response                  │
"   └─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
"
"   ┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
"   │  s:stored_input_tokens                                                  │
"   │                                                                         │
"   │  Set by ──── HandleStreamOutput()  on message_start event               │
"   │  Consumed by DisplayTokenUsageAndCost()  on message_delta event         │
"   │  Deleted by DisplayTokenUsageAndCost()  after use                       │
"   │                                                                         │
"   │  Bridges two separate SSE events that carry the two halves of the       │
"   │  token count (input tokens arrive first, output tokens arrive last)     │
"   └─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
"
"   ┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
"   │  s:last_token_usage   (formatted string)                                │
"   │                                                                         │
"   │  Set by ──── DisplayTokenUsageAndCost()  (also echom's it immediately)  │
"   │  Consumed by AppendTokenUsage()  (writes it into chat buffer)           │
"   │  Deleted by AppendTokenUsage()  after writing                           │
"   └─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
" ============================================================================


" ============================================================================
" Configuration variables
" ============================================================================
" Sets up all global config variables with defaults if not already defined.
" Users can override these in their .vimrc before the plugin loads.
" - g:claude_api_key: Anthropic API key for direct API access
" - g:claude_api_url: The endpoint URL for the Anthropic messages API
" - g:claude_model: The Claude model name to use (e.g. claude-sonnet-4-6)
" - g:claude_use_bedrock: If 1, use AWS Bedrock instead of direct Anthropic API
" - g:claude_use_1m_context: If 1, enables the 1M token context beta header
" - g:claude_bedrock_region: AWS region for Bedrock requests
" - g:claude_bedrock_model_id: Bedrock-specific model identifier string
" - g:claude_aws_profile: AWS credentials profile name (empty = use default)
" - g:claude_map_implement: Visual-mode keybinding that invokes `:ClaudeImplement` on the selected lines
" - g:claude_map_open_chat: Keybinding to open the chat window
" - g:claude_map_send_chat_message: Keybinding to send a chat message
" - g:claude_map_cancel_response: Keybinding to cancel an in-flight response
" ============================================================================


" ============================================================================
" Keybindings setup
" ============================================================================

" ============================================================================
" s:SetupClaudeKeybindings()
" ============================================================================
" Called once on VimEnter via an autocommand.
" Registers all user-facing Ex commands and sets up keybindings:
"   - ClaudeImplement: a range command taking an instruction string; calls
"     s:ClaudeImplement() on the visually selected lines.
"   - ClaudeChat: opens (or focuses) the Claude Chat window.
"   - ClaudeCancel: cancels any in-flight streaming Claude response.
" The keybindings are read from g:claude_map_* so users can remap them.
" ============================================================================

" ============================================================================
" s:ClaudeLoadPrompt(prompt_type)
" ============================================================================
" Reads a prompt template from a markdown file next to this script.
" The file is named  claude_<prompt_type>_prompt.md  (e.g.
" claude_system_prompt.md, claude_implement_prompt.md).
" Returns the file contents as a list of lines.
" Used to initialise g:claude_default_system_prompt and
" g:claude_implement_prompt at startup.
" ============================================================================


" ============================================================================
" Claude API
" ============================================================================

" ============================================================================
" s:ClaudeQueryInternal(messages, system_prompt, tools,
"                        stream_callback, final_callback)
" ============================================================================
" Core function that fires off an async HTTP request to the Claude API
" (or AWS Bedrock) and wires up callbacks for the streaming response.
"
" Parameters:
"   messages        – List of {role, content} dicts representing the
"                     conversation history in Anthropic API format.
"   system_prompt   – String inserted as the system turn.
"   tools           – List of tool-definition dicts (may be empty).
"   stream_callback – Funcref(delta) called repeatedly as text arrives.
"   final_callback  – Funcref() called once when the stream is complete.
"
" Behaviour differs by backend:
"   Bedrock: builds a command that invokes claude_bedrock_helper.py with
"            the relevant args (region, model-id, messages, system prompt,
"            optional tools, optional AWS profile).
"   Direct API: builds a curl command with the required Anthropic headers
"            (Content-Type, x-api-key, anthropic-version, optional 1M-context
"            beta header).  The JSON body is written to a temp file to avoid
"            shell argument-length limits, then passed to curl with
"            --data-binary @<tmpfile>.
"
" The job is started with job_start() (Vim) or jobstart() (Neovim), hooking
" stdout → s:HandleStreamOutput*, stderr → s:HandleJobError*, and
" exit → s:HandleJobExit*.  The job handle is returned to the caller so it
" can be stored for later cancellation.
" ============================================================================

" ============================================================================
" s:DisplayTokenUsageAndCost(json_data)
" ============================================================================
" Receives the JSON string from a message_delta SSE event (already extracted
" by s:HandleStreamOutput), decodes it, and prints a token-usage summary.
" Also accumulates s:total_input_tokens, s:total_cache_creation_tokens,
" s:total_cache_read_tokens, and s:total_output_tokens across tool-use turns
" before computing cost. and prints a one-line token-usage summary to the
" message area via echom, e.g.:
"   Token usage - Input: 1234 ($0.0037), Output: 456 ($0.0068)
" Pricing is looked up from the s:claude_pricing dict by g:claude_model
" (defaulting to $3/M input, $15/M output). Cache-creation tokens are billed
" at 1.25× and cache-read tokens at 0.10× the input rate.
" Input token count is taken from s:stored_input_tokens which was saved
" earlier when the 'message_start' event arrived; that script-local
" variable is deleted afterwards to avoid stale data.
" ============================================================================

" ============================================================================
" s:HandleStreamOutput(stream_callback, final_callback, channel, msg)
" ============================================================================
" Vim-flavour stdout callback. Receives raw text from curl's SSE stream,
" splits it on newlines, and dispatches each line:
"
"   event: ping                → silently ignored
"   event: error               → calls stream_callback with an error string,
"                                then final_callback
"   event: message_stop        → calls final_callback (stream is done)
"   event: message_start/…     → recognised event names, no further action
"   data: <json>               → decoded and handled by type:
"       message_start          → stores input_tokens, cache_creation_input_tokens,
"                                and cache_read_input_tokens from the usage block
"                                into s:stored_input_tokens, s:stored_cache_creation_tokens,
"                                and s:stored_cache_read_tokens respectively.
"       message_delta          → calls s:DisplayTokenUsageAndCost
"       content_block_start    → if content_block.type == 'tool_use', starts
"                                accumulating a new tool call in
"                                s:current_tool_call
"       content_block_delta /
"         input_json_delta     → appends partial JSON to s:current_tool_call.input
"       content_block_stop     → if a tool call was being built, decodes its
"                                input JSON and calls s:AppendToolUse to write
"                                it into the chat buffer
"       delta.text present     → calls stream_callback(delta) to stream text
"       anything else          → forwards raw line to stream_callback as a
"                                warning string
" ============================================================================

" ============================================================================
" s:HandleJobError / s:HandleJobErrorNvim
" ============================================================================
" Stderr callbacks (Vim / Neovim variants).
" Any text arriving on stderr is passed straight to stream_callback as an
" error string, then final_callback is invoked to clean up.
" ============================================================================

" ============================================================================
" s:HandleJobExit / s:HandleJobExitNvim
" ============================================================================
" Exit callbacks (Vim / Neovim variants).
" Always deletes the temporary JSON file that was written by
" s:ClaudeQueryInternal.  If the exit status is non-zero, reports an error
" via stream_callback and calls final_callback.
" ============================================================================

" ============================================================================
" s:HandleStreamOutputNvim / (Nvim wrappers)
" ============================================================================
" Neovim's job callbacks receive data as a list of strings rather than a
" single string, so these thin wrappers iterate over that list and delegate
" each item to the corresponding Vim-flavour handler above.
" ============================================================================

" ============================================================================
" s:HandleJobError / s:HandleJobErrorNvim
" ============================================================================
" Stderr callbacks (Vim / Neovim variants).
" Any text arriving on stderr is passed straight to stream_callback as an
" error string, then final_callback is invoked to clean up.
" ============================================================================

" ============================================================================
" s:HandleJobExit / s:HandleJobExitNvim
" ============================================================================
" Exit callbacks (Vim / Neovim variants).
" Always deletes the temporary JSON file that was written by
" s:ClaudeQueryInternal.  If the exit status is non-zero, reports an error
" via stream_callback and calls final_callback.
" ============================================================================


" ============================================================================
" Diff View
" ============================================================================

" ============================================================================
" s:ApplyChange(normal_command, content)
" ============================================================================
" Low-level helper that applies a text change to the current buffer by
" running an arbitrary Normal-mode command followed by pasting content via
" the expression register (<C-r>=).
" Saves and restores the window view and the 'paste' option so that
" auto-indentation does not corrupt the inserted text.
" The literal string '<CR>' inside normal_command is translated to a real
" carriage-return before execution.
" ============================================================================

" ============================================================================
" s:ApplyCodeChangesDiff(bufnr, changes)
" ============================================================================
" Opens a side-by-side diff showing the proposed edits for buffer `bufnr`.
"
" Steps:
"  1. Finds (or creates) a window that displays the target buffer. If the
"     buffer isn't currently visible in any window, it splits and switches
"     to it.
"  2. Opens a new scratch buffer to the right (rightbelow vnew), copies the
"     current content of the target buffer into it, and sets the same
"     filetype so syntax highlighting matches.
"  3. Iterates over the `changes` list and applies each one to the scratch
"     buffer:
"       type='content'  → calls s:ApplyChange() with a Normal-mode command
"                         and replacement text.
"       type='vimexec'  → runs each command string with :execute (falling
"                         back to :normal if :execute fails).
"     Failed edits are collected and reported as warnings but do not abort
"     the remaining changes.
"  4. Calls :diffthis on both the scratch buffer and the original buffer,
"     producing a standard Vim diff view. The user can then inspect the diff,
"     use :diffget / do to accept hunks, and :q to close the scratch buffer.
"  5. Returns to whatever window was active before this function was called.
" ============================================================================


" ============================================================================
" Tool Integration
" ============================================================================

" ============================================================================
" g:claude_tools  (configuration list)
" ============================================================================
" Defines the tools that Claude is allowed to call during a chat session.
" Each entry is a dict matching the Anthropic tool-definition schema:
"   name           – identifier Claude uses when it wants to call the tool
"   description    – natural-language description shown to the model
"   input_schema   – JSON-Schema object describing the expected arguments
"
" Built-in tools:
"   python    – runs a Python one-liner with `python3 -c` and returns stdout.
"   shell     – runs an arbitrary shell command and returns stdout + stderr
"               + exit status.
"   open      – opens a file/directory in a hidden Vim window and returns
"               the buffer name (or ERROR if the path doesn't exist / is
"               empty).
"   new       – creates a new empty file on disk, opens it in Vim, and
"               returns the buffer name (or ERROR if the file already
"               exists).
"   open_web  – fetches a URL with `elinks -dump` and returns the buffer
"               name of the scratch window containing the rendered text.
"   web_search– URL-encodes the query and delegates to open_web with a
"               Google search URL.
" ============================================================================

" ============================================================================
" s:ExecuteTool(tool_name, arguments)
" ============================================================================
" Dispatcher: maps the tool name string that Claude requested to the
" appropriate Vim function, passing the relevant argument fields.
" web_search is special-cased here: it percent-encodes the query string
" with a py3eval one-liner before forwarding to s:ExecuteOpenWebTool.
" Returns the string result that will be fed back to Claude as a tool
" result message.
" ============================================================================

" ============================================================================
" s:ExecutePythonCode(code)
" ============================================================================
" Asks the user for confirmation (y/n) before running `python3 -c <code>`.
" This safety prompt prevents Claude from executing arbitrary Python without
" user awareness. If the user approves, runs the code with system() and
" returns the combined output. If denied, returns a cancellation message
" which is sent back to Claude so it knows the execution didn't happen.
" The prompt also mentions C-C / C-] to guide the user on pause/resume.
" ============================================================================

" ============================================================================
" s:ExecuteShellCommand(command)
" ============================================================================
" Same confirmation pattern as s:ExecutePythonCode, but for shell commands.
" Runs the command with system(), captures stdout, and appends the numeric
" exit status on a final line so Claude can detect failures.
" ============================================================================

" ============================================================================
" s:ExecuteOpenTool(path)
" ============================================================================
" Opens `path` in a temporary top-left 1-line window using :edit.
" If the resulting buffer is empty (file not found or unreadable) the window
" is closed and an ERROR string is returned.
" Otherwise the window is left open (so its content is available as a
" buffer) and the buffer name is returned. The original window is restored
" in all cases.
" ============================================================================

" ============================================================================
" s:ExecuteNewTool(path)
" ============================================================================
" Guards against overwriting existing files by checking filereadable().
" If the file already exists, returns an ERROR string immediately.
" Otherwise opens a blank top-left window, writes it to disk with
" :silent write (creating the file), and returns the buffer name so
" Claude knows which buffer to target when writing content into the file.
" ============================================================================

" ============================================================================
" s:ExecuteOpenWebTool(url)
" ============================================================================
" Fetches url using `:r !elinks -dump` (a terminal browser that converts HTML
" to plain text) and places the result in a scratch buffer.
" The buffer is named after the URL so it can be referenced later.
" Returns the buffer name on success, or an ERROR string if elinks fails.
" Used both directly (open_web tool) and indirectly (web_search tool).
" ============================================================================


" ============================================================================
" ClaudeImplement
" ============================================================================

" ============================================================================
" s:LogImplementInChat(instruction, implement_response, bufname,
"                       start_line, end_line)
" ============================================================================
" Records a ClaudeImplement interaction in the chat window so there is a
" permanent, scrollable log of what was asked and what was generated.
" - Removes the trailing blank "You:" prompt line if present.
" - Appends a "You: Implement in <file> (lines N-M): <instruction>" line.
" - Shows the first and last lines of the selected range (with "..." in
"   between when the range is more than 2 lines) as context.
" - Appends Claude's full response via s:AppendResponse().
" - Calls s:CloseCurrentInteractionCodeBlocks() and s:PrepareNextInput()
"   to tidy up the chat buffer ready for the next message.
" ============================================================================

" ============================================================================
" s:ClaudeImplement(line1, line2, instruction)
" ============================================================================
" Entry point for the :ClaudeImplement range command (mapped to <leader>ci
" in visual mode by default).
"
" 1. Collects the lines in the visual selection as a single string.
" 2. Builds a system prompt by wrapping the selected code in <code>…</code>
"    tags and appending the contents of claude_implement_prompt.md.
"    This prompt instructs Claude to return its answer as a fenced code block.
" 3. Sends a single-turn message (the user's instruction) to Claude with no
"    tools enabled, using s:ClaudeQueryInternal.
" 4. Streams the response into s:implement_response via
"    s:StreamingImplementResponse, then on completion calls
"    s:FinalImplementResponse to extract and apply the code.
" Function to implement code based on instructions
" ============================================================================

" ============================================================================
" s:ExtractCodeFromMarkdown(markdown)
" ============================================================================
" Strips the fenced code block delimiters (``` lines) from a markdown string
" and returns only the code inside the first code block found.
" Used by s:FinalImplementResponse to pull the bare code out of Claude's
" markdown-formatted reply before inserting it into the buffer.
" ============================================================================

" ============================================================================
" s:StreamingImplementResponse(delta)
" ============================================================================
" Stream callback for ClaudeImplement. Simply accumulates all arriving text
" deltas into the script-local s:implement_response string. No UI update is
" done during streaming for implement — the result is only shown once the
" full response has arrived.
" ============================================================================

" ============================================================================
" s:FinalImplementResponse(line1, line2, bufnr, bufname, winid, instruction)
" ============================================================================
" Final callback for ClaudeImplement, called when the stream ends.
" 1. Returns to the original window where the implement command was invoked.
" 2. Logs the full interaction in the chat window via s:LogImplementInChat.
" 3. Extracts the bare code from the markdown response with
"    s:ExtractCodeFromMarkdown.
" 4. Builds a single 'content' change that replaces the originally selected
"    lines (line1 to line2) with the extracted code, using a Visual-mode
"    selection + 'c' (change) as the Normal-mode command.
" 5. Passes that change to s:ApplyCodeChangesDiff() to show the result in a
"    side-by-side diff view so the user can review before accepting.
" 6. Prints a hint reminding the user how to work with the diff (:diffget /
"    do to accept hunks, :q to close).
" 7. Cleans up s:implement_response and s:current_chat_job.
" ============================================================================


" ============================================================================
" ClaudeChat
" ============================================================================


" ----- Chat service functions

" ============================================================================
" s:GetOrCreateChatWindow()
" ============================================================================
" Ensures the Claude Chat buffer exists and is loaded. If it doesn't exist
" yet (bufnr returns -1) or has been unloaded, calls s:OpenClaudeChat() to
" create it fresh. Returns a three-element list:
"   [chat_bufnr, chat_winid, current_winid]
" where current_winid is the window that was active before this call, so
" callers can restore it with win_gotoid() when they are done.
" ============================================================================

" ============================================================================
" s:GetClaudeIndent()
" ============================================================================
" Returns the string used to indent continuation lines inside the chat
" buffer. Respects the buffer's expandtab / shiftwidth / tabstop settings:
"   expandtab on  → returns shiftwidth spaces
"   expandtab off → returns the appropriate number of tab characters
" This indentation is used to visually mark lines that belong to a Claude
" or Tool response, and is also relied upon by the parser to distinguish
" continuation lines from new speaker lines.
" ============================================================================

" ============================================================================
" s:AppendResponse(response)
" ============================================================================
" Appends a complete Claude response to the current buffer (expected to be
" the chat buffer).
" - Single-line response: appended as "Claude: <text>" on one line.
" - Multi-line response: starts with a bare "Claude:" line, then each
"   subsequent line is indented with s:GetClaudeIndent(). Blank lines are
"   preserved as empty strings (no indent added) to keep paragraph spacing.
" ============================================================================

" ----- Chat window UX

" ============================================================================
" GetChatFold(lnum)
" ============================================================================
" Fold-expression function intended for use with 'foldmethod=expr' in the
" chat buffer (set via 'setlocal foldexpr=GetChatFold(v:lnum)').
" Returns a fold-level descriptor string for each line, following Vim's
" foldexpr conventions:
"
"   '0'   → not part of any fold (terminates any open fold)
"   '='   → same fold level as the previous line (continue current fold)
"   '>1'  → start a new level-1 fold on this line
"   '>2'  → start a new level-2 fold on this line (nested inside level-1)
"   '<2'  → end a level-2 fold on this line
"
" The intended fold structure is:
"   Level 1 folds: each complete "You:" / "System prompt:" interaction block,
"                  so entire exchanges can be collapsed in the chat history.
"   Level 2 folds: fenced code blocks (``` ... ```) nested inside a level-1
"                  fold, so individual code snippets can be collapsed
"                  independently while keeping the surrounding text visible.
"
" Rules applied per line:
"   "^You:" or "^System prompt:"  → '>1' (start a new top-level fold)
"   indented, blank, or "^.*:"    → '=' by default (continue current fold),
"                                   UNLESS the line is "^\s*```":
"                                     if already at level 1 → '>2' (open code fold)
"                                     otherwise             → '<2' (close code fold)
"   anything else                 → '0' (outside any fold)
" ============================================================================

" ============================================================================
" g:SetupClaudeChatSyntax()
" ============================================================================
" Defines the syntax highlighting rules for the Claude Chat buffer.
" Only runs once per buffer (guarded by b:current_syntax).
" Includes the standard markdown syntax as a sub-syntax (@markdown group)
" so that Claude's responses render with markdown highlighting.
" Defines these additional regions/matches on top:
"   claudeChatSystem        – the indented system-prompt block at the top
"   claudeChatSystemKeyword – the "System prompt:" label itself
"   claudeChatYou           – "You:" speaker label
"   claudeChatClaude        – "Claude:" / "Claude...:" speaker label
"   claudeChatToolUse       – "Tool use (...):" label
"   claudeChatToolResult    – "Tool result (...):" label
"   claudeChatCodeBlock     – fenced code blocks inside responses (no spell)
" Also clears markdownCodeBlock to prevent indented lines from being treated
" as code blocks by the markdown sub-syntax (which would over-match here).
" ============================================================================

" ============================================================================
" s:GoToLastYouLine()
" ============================================================================
" Moves the cursor to the end of the last line of the buffer (G$).
" Used as a BufWinEnter autocommand so that every time the chat window is
" displayed the cursor is positioned at the active "You:" input line at the
" bottom, ready for the user to type.
" ============================================================================

" ============================================================================
" s:OpenClaudeChat()
" ============================================================================
" Opens the Claude Chat window or focuses it if already open.
"
" First-time open (buffer doesn't exist yet):
"   1. Creates a new bottom-right window ('botright new') named 'Claude Chat'.
"   2. Configures it as a scratch buffer (buftype=nofile, noswapfile,
"      bufhidden=hide) with linebreak wrapping for readability.
"   3. Calls g:SetupClaudeChatSyntax() to apply chat-specific highlighting.
"   4. Populates the buffer with:
"        - The system prompt (from g:claude_default_system_prompt), with
"          each continuation line tab-indented.
"        - A usage hint line.
"        - A blank line followed by an initial "You: " prompt.
"   5. Registers a BufWinEnter autocommand that keeps the cursor at the
"      bottom whenever the window is re-entered.
"   6. Registers the buffer-local C-] mapping (g:claude_map_send_chat_message)
"      for both insert and normal mode to call s:SendChatMessage('Claude:').
"
" Subsequent opens (buffer already loaded):
"   - If the buffer is visible in a window, moves focus there.
"   - If the buffer is loaded but not displayed, splits and shows it.
"
" In both cases finishes by calling s:GoToLastYouLine().
" ============================================================================

" ----- Chat parser (to messages list)

" ============================================================================
" s:AddMessageToList(messages, message)
" ============================================================================
" Finalises a message dict that was being accumulated by the parser and
" appends it to the messages list (only if role is non-empty).
" Handles three cases:
"   Plain text message   → {role, content: joined string}
"   Message with tool_use→ content becomes a list:
"                          [{type:'text', text:…}, <tool_use dict>]
"   Message with tool_result → content becomes a list containing just
"                          the tool_result dict (as required by the API).
" NOTE: currently only handles one tool_use or tool_result per message.
" ============================================================================

" ============================================================================
" s:InitMessage(role, line)
" ============================================================================
" Creates a fresh message accumulator dict for the given role ('user' or
" 'assistant'). The first line's speaker prefix (e.g. "You: ", "Claude: ")
" is stripped with a regex, and the remaining text becomes the first element
" of the content list. tool_use and tool_result are initialised to empty
" dicts so the parser can check emptiness with !empty().
" ============================================================================

" ============================================================================
" s:ParseToolUse(line)
" ============================================================================
" Parses a "Tool use (<id>): <name>" line from the chat buffer back into a
" tool_use dict suitable for the Anthropic API:
"   { type: 'tool_use', id: <id>, name: <name>, input: {} }
" Returns an empty dict if the line doesn't match the expected format.
" ============================================================================

" ============================================================================
" s:InitToolResult(line)
" ============================================================================
" Parses a "Tool result (<id>):" line and creates a fresh message
" accumulator whose tool_result field holds a skeleton tool_result dict:
"   { type: 'tool_result', tool_use_id: <id>, content: '' }
" Subsequent indented lines will be appended to content by s:AppendContent.
" ============================================================================

" ============================================================================
" s:AppendContent(message, line)
" ============================================================================
" Appends a continuation line to the message currently being accumulated,
" routing it to the right place depending on message state:
"
"   tool_use present + line matches "Input:" → decodes the JSON on that line
"                                              and stores it as tool_use.input
"   tool_use present + tool is 'python'      → strips indentation and appends
"                                              to tool_use.input.code (handles
"                                              multi-line Python snippets)
"   tool_result present                      → strips indent and appends to
"                                              tool_result.content string
"   plain message                            → strips indent, also strips any
"                                              trailing " [APPLIED]" marker
"                                              that `s:ProcessCodeBlock`
"                                              appended to the opening ` ```
"                                              `header line of an already-
"                                              applied code block, before
"                                              adding the line to content.,
"                                              then appends to the message's
"                                              content list.
" ============================================================================

" ============================================================================
" s:ProcessLine(line, messages, current_message)
" ============================================================================
" The core line-by-line state machine of the chat buffer parser.
" Works on a copy of current_message and returns the (possibly new)
" accumulator. Recognises these speaker-prefix patterns:
"
"   "You:"         → finalises current_message into messages, starts a new
"                    'user' accumulator via s:InitMessage.
"   "Claude" (any) → finalises current_message, starts a new 'assistant'
"                    accumulator. Matches both "Claude:" and "Claude...:"
"                    (the latter is used for tool-only responses).
"   "Tool use ("   → does NOT finalise; instead calls s:ParseToolUse and
"                    stores the result in current_message.tool_use, so the
"                    tool call is attached to the preceding Claude message.
"   "Tool result (" → finalises current_message, starts a fresh user message
"                    whose tool_result field is populated via s:InitToolResult.
"   anything else  → if a message is in progress, delegates to
"                    s:AppendContent to accumulate the line as content.
" ============================================================================

" ============================================================================
" s:ParseChatBuffer()
" ============================================================================
" Reads the entire chat buffer from line 1 to '$' and converts it into the
" data structures the Anthropic API expects.
"
" Two-pass concerns handled in a single linear scan:
"   - Lines beginning with "System prompt:" start the system prompt block;
"     subsequent indented lines are accumulated into l:system_prompt.
"   - Once a non-indented, non-system-prompt line is seen, system prompt
"     parsing ends and the conversation parser (s:ProcessLine) takes over.
"
" Returns a two-element list:
"   [ messages, system_prompt_string ]
" where messages is the filtered list produced by s:ProcessLine (empty
" content entries are removed) and system_prompt_string is the system prompt
" lines joined with newlines.
" ============================================================================

" ----- Sending messages

" ============================================================================
" s:GetBuffersContent()
" ============================================================================
" Collects the content of every listed, visible, non-chat buffer and returns
" it as a list of {name, contents} dicts. "Visible" means the buffer has at
" least one open window (win_findbuf returns non-empty).
" This list is used by s:SendChatMessage to prepend all open buffer contents
" to the system prompt, giving Claude full awareness of the current workspace.
" ============================================================================

" ============================================================================
" s:SendChatMessage(prefix)
" ============================================================================
" The main entry point for sending a user message. Called when the user
" presses C-] (or the configured keybinding) in the chat window.
" Also called recursively by s:FinalChatResponse when tool results need to
" be sent back to Claude.
"
" Steps:
"  1. Calls s:ParseChatBuffer() to get the current messages + system prompt.
"  2. Checks whether the last assistant message contains any tool_use blocks
"     (via s:ResponseExtractToolUses). If so, executes each tool with
"     s:ExecuteTool, appends the result to the chat buffer via
"     s:AppendToolResult, then re-parses the buffer so the tool results are
"     included in the messages sent to the API.
"  3. Builds a buffer-content preamble (s:GetBuffersContent) and prepends it
"     to the system prompt so Claude can see all open files.
"  4. Appends a "<prefix> " placeholder line to the chat buffer and moves
"     the cursor there, so the user can see the response appearing in real
"     time as it streams in.
"  5. Fires off the async API call via s:ClaudeQueryInternal, using
"     s:StreamingChatResponse as the stream callback and
"     s:FinalChatResponse as the final callback.
"  6. Stores the job handle in s:current_chat_job so it can be cancelled
"     via s:CancelClaudeResponse.
" ============================================================================

" ----- Handling responses: Tool use

" ============================================================================
" s:ResponseExtractToolUses(messages)
" ============================================================================
" Inspects the last message in the messages list. If its content is a list
" (i.e. it contains structured blocks rather than plain text) it filters and
" returns only the entries whose type is 'tool_use'. Returns an empty list
" if there are no messages, if the last message has plain-text content, or
" if there are no tool_use blocks.
" Used both in s:SendChatMessage (to decide whether to execute tools before
" sending) and in s:FinalChatResponse (to decide whether to auto-continue).
" ============================================================================

" ============================================================================
" s:AppendToolUse(tool_call_id, tool_name, tool_input)
" ============================================================================
" Writes a tool-use record into the chat buffer in the format the parser
" can later reconstruct:
"   Tool use (<id>): <name>
"     <indented representation of input>
" For the 'python' tool, the code is written line-by-line (indented) so it
" is human-readable in the chat log. For all other tools, the input dict is
" serialised as a single JSON line prefixed with "Input: ".
" Also handles the edge case where the preceding "Claude: " line is empty
" (a tool-only response with no text): rewrites it to
" "Claude...: (tool-only response)" so the parser still recognises it as an
" assistant turn.
" ============================================================================

" ============================================================================
" s:AppendToolResult(tool_call_id, result)
" ============================================================================
" Writes a tool-result record into the chat buffer:
"   Tool result (<id>):
"     <indented result lines>
" Each line of the result string is individually indented so the parser can
" reconstruct the full multi-line result when it encounters these lines via
" s:AppendContent.
" ============================================================================

" ----- Handling responses: Code changes

" ============================================================================
" s:ProcessCodeBlock(block, all_changes)
" ============================================================================
" Processes a single fenced code block found in the latest Claude response
" and registers it as a pending change in the all_changes dict.
"
" The code block header (the text after the opening ```) is expected to
" follow the convention:  <filetype> <buffername>[:<normal_command>]
"   filetype       – used to set the scratch buffer's filetype in the diff
"                    view; if 'vimexec', the block is treated as Vim commands
"                    rather than file content.
"   buffername     – matched against open buffers with bufnr(); changes are
"                    grouped by buffer number in all_changes.
"   normal_command – optional Normal-mode command controlling where the
"                    content is inserted (defaults to 'Go<CR>' which appends
"                    at end of file).
"
" For 'vimexec' blocks, adds a {type:'vimexec', commands:[…]} entry.
" For content blocks, adds a {type:'content', normal_command:…, content:…}
" entry. In both cases, marks the opening ``` line in the chat buffer with
" " [APPLIED]" so the parser knows not to re-apply it on the next send.
" ============================================================================

" ============================================================================
" s:ResponseExtractChanges()
" ============================================================================
" Scans the most recent Claude response block in the chat buffer (from the
" last "Claude:" line to end of buffer) looking for fenced code blocks whose
" headers follow the <filetype> <buffername>[:<command>] convention.
" Builds and returns an all_changes dict keyed by buffer number, where each
" value is a list of change dicts ready for s:ApplyCodeChangesDiff.
" Handles unclosed code blocks (e.g. if the stream was cancelled mid-block)
" by treating end-of-buffer as the implicit closing delimiter.
" ============================================================================

" ============================================================================
" s:ApplyChangesFromResponse()
" ============================================================================
" Calls s:ResponseExtractChanges() and, if any code-block changes were
" found, iterates over the all_changes dict and calls s:ApplyCodeChangesDiff
" for each target buffer, passing its list of changes. After processing all
" buffers, moves the cursor to the end of the chat buffer with G.
" Called at the end of every complete Claude response to automatically
" surface any code edits the model proposed.
" ============================================================================

" ----- Handling responses

" ============================================================================
" s:ClosePreviousFold()
" ============================================================================
" Intended to be called after a complete Claude response has been appended
" to the chat buffer, in order to collapse the just-finished interaction
" fold so the chat log stays compact.
"
" Saves the cursor position, then navigates with '[z' (move to the start of
" the current fold) and 'k' (up one line) and '[z' again followed by 'zc'
" (close fold) to collapse the previous interaction's level-1 fold.
" The cursor is restored to its saved position afterwards.
"
" Emits a warning if the fold at the target line is not actually closed
" after the attempt (foldclosed('.') == -1 means no fold is closed there).
" ============================================================================

" ============================================================================
" s:CloseCurrentInteractionCodeBlocks()
" ============================================================================
" Placeholder / hook for fold management. Currently the folding code is
" commented out, but the function still saves and restores the cursor
" position and navigates to the start of the current fold with [z.
" Its intended purpose (when folding is re-enabled) is to collapse all
" level-2 folds (i.e. code blocks) within the current interaction so that
" the chat log stays compact after a response is complete.
" ============================================================================

" ============================================================================
" s:PrepareNextInput()
" ============================================================================
" Appends two lines to the chat buffer — a blank separator line and a fresh
" "You: " prompt — then moves the cursor to the end of that line (G$).
" Called after every complete response (and after cancellation) to leave the
" chat buffer in a state where the user can immediately start typing their
" next message.
" ============================================================================

" ============================================================================
" s:StreamingChatResponse(delta)
" ============================================================================
" Stream callback for chat responses. Called repeatedly with small text
" deltas as they arrive from the API.
"
" For each delta:
"  1. Ensures the chat window is open via s:GetOrCreateChatWindow and
"     temporarily moves focus there.
"  2. Splits the delta on newlines (keeping trailing empty strings with the
"     keepempty flag so that a trailing newline produces a new line).
"  3. Appends the first segment of the delta onto the current last line of
"     the buffer (no newline inserted — this continues the current line).
"  4. Any additional segments (i.e. text after a newline in the delta) are
"     appended as new indented lines.
"  5. Moves the cursor to the bottom (G) so the user sees output scroll in
"     real time, then restores focus to the original window.
" ============================================================================

" ============================================================================
" s:FinalChatResponse()
" ============================================================================
" Final callback invoked once when the Claude stream ends completely.
"
"  1. Parses the chat buffer to get the latest messages list.
"  2. Checks whether the last assistant message contains tool_use blocks.
"  3. Calls s:ApplyChangesFromResponse() to process any code-block edits
"     embedded in the response.
"  4a. If tool uses were found: calls s:SendChatMessage('Claude...:') to
"      immediately execute the tools and send a follow-up request. The
"      'Claude...:' prefix signals that this is a continuation turn rather
"      than a fresh user message.
"  4b. If no tool uses: the interaction is complete. Calls
"      s:CloseCurrentInteractionCodeBlocks() to tidy up any folds, appends
"      a fresh "You: " prompt via s:PrepareNextInput(), restores the
"      original window, and clears s:current_chat_job.
" ============================================================================

" ============================================================================
" s:AppendTokenUsage()
" ============================================================================
" A small function that writes `s:last_token_usage` into the chat buffer as
" a comment-style line, then clears it. Only acts if the variable exists (so
" it's safe to call unconditionally):
" Prints the token usage and cost in the chat.
" ============================================================================

" ============================================================================
" s:CancelClaudeResponse()
" ============================================================================
" Cancels any in-flight streaming response, bound to <leader>cx by default.
" If s:current_chat_job exists:
"   Neovim → calls jobstop() with the job ID.
"   Vim    → calls ch_close() with the channel handle.
" After stopping the job, clears s:current_chat_job, appends a
" "[Response cancelled by user]" notice to the chat buffer via
" s:AppendResponse, tidies up folds/code blocks, and adds a fresh "You: "
" prompt so the user can continue the conversation.
" If no job is running, prints a message saying there is nothing to cancel.
" ============================================================================

" ============================================================================
" s:ClaudeBatchPoll(batch_id, custom_id)
" ============================================================================
" Polls the batch API for results. Schedules itself via timer every
" g:claude_batch_poll_interval seconds until the batch ends.
" When complete, appends the result to the chat buffer.
" ============================================================================



"------------------------------------------------------------------------------
" Updates to support interacting with Qwen (local AI)
"------------------------------------------------------------------------------

" ============================================================================
" s:GetAllBufferContents()
" ============================================================================
" Iterates over every buffer slot (1 to bufnr('$')) and collects the content
" of each existing, non-empty buffer into a list of dictionaries.
" Each dictionary contains:
"   'filename'  – the buffer name, or '[No Name]' if unnamed.
"   'content'   – the full buffer text joined with newlines.
"   'buffer_id' – the buffer number.
" Buffers that do not exist or whose trimmed content is empty are skipped.
" Returns the list of buffer dictionaries.
" ============================================================================

" ============================================================================
" s:FormatAllBuffersForPrompt()
" ============================================================================
" Calls s:GetAllBufferContents() and formats the result as a single string
" suitable for injection into an LLM prompt.
" Each buffer is rendered as:
"   # Contents of <filename>
"   <content>
"   <buffer text>
"   </content>
" Sections are separated by a blank line.
" Returns the formatted string.
" ============================================================================

" ============================================================================
" s:CallQwenAsync(prompt)
" ============================================================================
" Sends a prompt to the Ollama /api/generate endpoint asynchronously using
" curl, with streaming enabled (stream: true).
" Builds a JSON payload containing:
"   'model'   – g:ai_model
"   'prompt'  – the supplied prompt string
"   'options' – num_ctx (g:ollama_num_ctx) and num_predict (g:ollama_num_predict)
" Writes the payload to a temp file and launches curl via:
"   Neovim → jobstart(), wiring stdout/stderr/exit to the Nvim handler trio.
"   Vim    → job_start(), wiring out_cb/err_cb/exit_cb to the Vim handler trio.
" Stores the running job handle in s:current_chat_job.
" ============================================================================

" ============================================================================
" s:HandleQwenStreamChunk(msg)
" ============================================================================
" Parses a raw chunk of text received from the Ollama streaming response.
" Splits the input on newlines and attempts to JSON-decode each non-empty
" line (JSONL format).  For each successfully decoded object:
"   - Extracts the 'response' field and passes any non-empty token to
"     s:StreamingChatResponse() so it is appended to the chat buffer.
"   - If the 'done' field is truthy, calls s:FinalQwenResponse() to
"     close out the interaction.
" Lines that fail JSON decoding are silently skipped.
" ============================================================================

" ============================================================================
" s:HandleQwenStream(channel, msg)
" ============================================================================
" Vim-specific stdout callback for the curl job.
" Receives a channel handle and a message string, then delegates directly
" to s:HandleQwenStreamChunk() for JSONL parsing and UI updates.
" ============================================================================

" ============================================================================
" s:HandleQwenError(channel, msg)
" ============================================================================
" Vim-specific stderr callback for the curl job.
" If the message is non-empty, surfaces it to the user by prepending
" 'Error: ' and passing it to s:StreamingChatResponse(), then calls
" s:FinalQwenResponse() to close the interaction cleanly.
" ============================================================================

" ============================================================================
" s:HandleQwenExit(tmp_file, job, status)
" ============================================================================
" Vim-specific exit callback for the curl job.
" Always deletes the temporary JSON payload file (a:tmp_file).
" If the exit status is non-zero, appends an error notice via
" s:StreamingChatResponse() and calls s:FinalQwenResponse().
" ============================================================================

" ============================================================================
" s:HandleQwenStreamNvim(job_id, data, event)
" ============================================================================
" Neovim-specific stdout callback for the curl job.
" Iterates over the list of strings in a:data (Neovim passes stdout chunks
" as a list) and delegates each entry to s:HandleQwenStreamChunk().
" ============================================================================

" ============================================================================
" s:HandleQwenErrorNvim(job_id, data, event)
" ============================================================================
" Neovim-specific stderr callback for the curl job.
" Iterates over a:data and, for each non-empty string, surfaces an error
" via s:StreamingChatResponse() and closes the interaction with
" s:FinalQwenResponse().
" ============================================================================

" ============================================================================
" s:HandleQwenExitNvim(tmp_file, job_id, exit_code, event)
" ============================================================================
" Neovim-specific exit callback for the curl job.
" Adapts Neovim's four-argument signature to the shared s:HandleQwenExit()
" implementation by forwarding tmp_file and exit_code (passing 0 as a
" placeholder for the unused job argument).
" ============================================================================

" ============================================================================
" s:FinalQwenResponse()
" ============================================================================
" Finalises a completed (or errored) Ollama streaming interaction.
" Guards against double-invocation (which can occur when both the 'done'
" JSON field and the job exit callback fire) using the flag
" s:qwen_response_finalized; returns immediately if already set.
" When called for the first time:
"   - Calls s:CloseCurrentInteractionCodeBlocks() to tidy any open folds.
"   - Calls s:PrepareNextInput() to append a fresh 'You: ' prompt.
"   - Cleans up s:current_chat_job and s:qwen_response_finalized.
" ============================================================================

